  "prompt": "In Tagalog, what are the rules for using Nang and Ng?",
  "response": "In Tagalog, \"nang\" and \"ng\" are two very commonly used particles, but they serve different grammatical functions. Here's a breakdown of their uses:\n\n### Nang\n\n1. **Adverb of time**: \"Nang\" is used to indicate the past tense. It translates to \"when\" or \"at the time that.\"\n   - Example: **Nang** umalis siya, umiyak ako. (When he left, I cried.)\n\n2. **Adverb of manner**: \"Nang\" is used to describe how an action is done, translating to \"in a way that\" or \"to the extent that.\" It can also mean \"than\" in comparisons.\n   - Example: Tumakbo siya **nang** mabilis. (He ran fast.)\n   - Example: Mas mataas siya **nang** dalawang pulgada kaysa sa akin. (He is two inches taller than me.)\n\n3. **Conjunction**: \"Nang\" can be used as a conjunction meaning \"so that\" or \"in order that.\"\n   - Example: Mag-aral ka **nang** makapasa ka sa pagsusulit. (Study so that you can pass the exam.)\n\n### Ng\n\n1. **Possessive particle**: \"Ng\" is used to indicate possession, similar to the English apostrophe-s ('s).\n   - Example: Ang libro **ng** estudyante. (The student's book.)\n\n2. **Object marker**: \"Ng\" is used to mark the object of the verb, usually in non-focus constructions.\n   - Example: Kumain ako **ng** mansanas. (I ate an apple.)\n\n3. **Preposition**: \"Ng\" can serve as a preposition meaning \"of,\" \"from,\" or \"by.\"\n   - Example: Isang tasa **ng** kape. (A cup of coffee.)\n   - Example: Galing siya **ng** Pilipinas. (He is from the Philippines.)\n\n### Key Differences\n\n- **Nang** is used for time, manner, and as a conjunction. It is always pronounced with a long \"a\" sound.\n- **Ng** is used for possession, object marking, and as a preposition. It is pronounced with a shorter, sharper sound.\n\n### Examples to Illustrate the Difference\n\n- **Nang** (time): **Nang** dumating siya, natulog na ako. (When he arrived, I was already asleep.)\n- **Ng** (possession): Ang bahay **ng** lola ko. (My grandmother's house.)\n- **Nang** (manner): Kumanta siya **nang** maganda. (She sang beautifully.)\n- **Ng** (object): Binili ko **ng** regalo siya. (I bought her a gift.)\n\nUnderstanding the context is crucial in determining whether to use \"nang\" or \"ng\" correctly in Tagalog sentences.",
